body:
(This comes from a [Reddit thread](https://www.reddit.com/r/rust/comments/at6793/why_is_the_iter_version_performance_so_much/).)

In the code below, `slow` takes double the time `fast` takes. If `print` is changed to take a value rather than reference, the difference goes away.

```rust
fn print(s: &u64) {
    println!("{}", s);
}
fn fast() {
    let mut s: u64 = 0;
    for x in 0..10000000000 {
        if x % 16 < 4 {
            s += x;
        }
    }
    let s = s;
    print(&s);
}
fn slow() {
    let mut s: u64 = 0;
    for x in 0..10000000000 {
        if x % 16 < 4 {
            s += x;
        }
    }
    print(&s);
}
fn main() {
    if std::env::var("FAST").is_ok() {
        fast();
    } else {
        slow();
    }
}
```

Timings:
```
$ rustc -O main.rs
$ time FAST=1 ./main
12499999983750000000

real	0m4.334s
user	0m4.328s
sys	0m0.001s
$ time ./main
12499999983750000000

real	0m8.788s
user	0m8.776s
sys	0m0.002s
```
